My symptoms are currently managed by medication. But, it was extremely difficult prior to finding an effective medication. I have two relatives that died from likely suicide and also had Schizophrenia spectrum mental illness. I also have a background of working with people on the Autism spectrum. I developed a theory that estrogen fluctuations are related and the feelings are simply how we conceptualize glitchy sensory processing. Once I realized the likely neurohormonal condition of what I experienced, it allowed me to be more accepting of diagnosis and to acknowledge but frame symptoms as more benign & physiological than threatening. I also noticed that my ability to locate the direction a sound was coming from very poor. So, sound became very confusing as I misattributed who/what was producing the sound, interpreted half-heard conversation as being related to me, as people who begin to lose their hearing or who do not understand the language do. I'm interested in contributing to better understand, treat, and  decrease stigma for people experiencing psychosis.
